xxl.collections
Class StackQueue

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--xxl.collections.AbstractQueue
        |
        +--xxl.collections.StackQueue
public class StackQueue
extends AbstractQueue
implements LIFOQueue

This class provides an implementation of the Queue interface with a LIFO (last in, first out) strategy that internally uses a stack to store its elements. It implements the peek method but not the remove method.

Usage example (1). 

     // create a new stack queue

     StackQueue queue = new StackQueue();

     // create an iteration over 20 random Integers (between 0 and 100)

     Cursor cursor = new RandomIntegers(100, 20);

     // insert all elements of the given iterator

     queue.insertAll(cursor);

     // print all elements of the queue

     while (queue.hasNext())
         System.out.println(queue.next());

     // close the open queue and cursor after use

     queue.close();
     cursor.close();
Usage example (2). 
     // create an iteration over the Integer between 0 and 19

     cursor = new Enumerator(20);

     // create a new stack queue that uses a new stack to store its elements and that contains
     // all elements of the given iterator

     queue = (StackQueue)StackQueue.FACTORY_METHOD.invoke(cursor);

     // print all elements of the queue

     while (queue.hasNext())
         System.out.println(queue.next());

     // close the open queue and cursor after use

     queue.close();
     cursor.close();

Field Detail

FACTORY_METHOD

public static final Function FACTORY_METHOD
A factory method to create a new StackQueue (see contract for FACTORY_METHOD in interface Queue). It may be invoked with an array (parameter list) (for further details see Function) of stacks, an iterator or without any parameters. An array (parameter list) of stacks will be used to initialize the internally used stack with the stack at index 0 and an iterator will be used to insert the contained elements into the new StackQueue.
